  "verdict": "Same confidence-gated cascade, two cue-free tasks, opposite outcomes -- and the difference is CALIBRATION. TELEGRAPHED: CUE-FREE CASCADE WORKS -- the silo is CALIBRATED (ECE 0.05, conf-vs-correct AUC 0.90: it is uncertain exactly when it is wrong), so its confidence routes the hard regime to plain with NO cue. It closes 100% of the silo->plain gap (0.62->0.92, plain 0.92) at 45.3 avg attention pairs vs plain's 64 -- 29% cheaper -- escalating 90% of order but 0% of bag. ENTANGLED: NO HEADROOM -- plain 0.69 is barely above silo 0.68 (gap 1%). When the regime is illegible in the content, NEITHER expert can do the hard half cue-free, so a cascade has nothing better to escalate to -- and the silo's confidence is weak anyway (ECE 0.12, conf-vs-correct AUC 0.59). The cascade correctly stays cheap (~18.5 pairs) but cannot manufacture accuracy neither expert has. The lesson: a confidence cascade does not detect the hard regime -- it detects the cheap model's own UNCERTAINTY, which only helps when that uncertainty lines up with its errors (low ECE, AUC >> 0.5). And calibration here tracks LEGIBILITY: when the regime shows up in the content (telegraphed), the silo is calibrated AND a capable fallback exists, so you get cue-free routing for free; when it doesn't (entangled), the silo is confidently wrong AND nothing better exists to route to. This is the honest sequel to v5's catch 'the regime must be detectable in the input': if it is detectable in the CONTENT, you need neither a cue token nor a learned router -- a confidence cascade suffices; if it isn't, nothing does. Constructed contrast, tiny models, synthetic -- a demonstration of WHEN cascades work, not a benchmark."
}